ublication types MeSH terms Substances LinkOut - more resources\n\nReview\n\nBMC Womens Health\n\nActions\n\n-   [Search in PubMed](/?term=%22BMC+Womens+Health%22%5Bjour%5D&sort=date&sort_order=desc)\n-   [Search in NLM Catalog](https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/nlmcatalog?term=%22BMC+Womens+Health%22%5BTitle+Abbreviation%5D)\n-   [Add to Search](#)\n\n. 2024 Aug 7;24(1):445.\n\ndoi: 10.1186/s12905-024-03285-8.\n\n# Pseudo-Meigs syndrome caused by a rapidly enlarging hydropic leiomyoma with elevated CA125 levels mimicking ovarian malignancy: a case report and literature review\n\n[Longquan Zou](/?term=Zou+L&cauthor_id=39112955)  [1](#full-view-affiliation-1 \"Department of Pathology, Zigong Fourth People's Hospital, Zigong, Sichuan, China.\")   [2](#full-view-affiliation-2 \"Institute of Precision Medicine, Zigong Academy of Medical Big Data and Artificial Intelligence, Zigong, Sichuan, China.\") , [Jinlong Lou](/?term=Lou+J&cauthor_id=39112955)  [1](#full-view-affiliation-1 \"Department of Pathology, Zigong Fourth People's Hospital, Zigong, Sichuan, China.\")   [3](#full-view-affiliation-3 \"Department of General Surgery, Zigong Fourth People's Hospital, Zigong, Sichuan, China.\") , [Haoran Huang](/?term=Huang+H&cauthor_id=39112955)  [4](#full-view-affiliation-4 \"College of Biomedical Engineering, Chongqing Medical University, Chongqing, China.\") , [Lian Xu](/?term=Xu+L&cauthor_id=39112955)  [5](#full-view-affiliation-5 \"Department of Pathology, Key Laboratory of Birth Defects and Related Diseases of Women and Children of MOE, West China Second University Hospital, Sichuan University, Chengdu, Sichuan, China. Lian_xu@163.com.\")\n\nAffiliations Expand\n\n### Affiliations\n\n-   1 Department of Pathology, Zigong Fourth People's Hospital, Zigong, Sichuan, China.\n-   2 Institute of Precision Medicine, Zigong Academy of Medical Big Data and Artificial Intelligence, Zigong, Sichuan, China.\n-   3 Department of General Surgery, Zigong Fourth People's Hospital, Zigong, Sichuan, China.\n-   4 College of Biomedical Engineering, Chongqing Medical University, Chongqing, China.\n-   5 Department of Pathology, Key Laboratory of Birth Defects and Related Diseases of Women and Children of MOE, West China Second University Hospital, Sichuan University, Chengdu, Sichuan, China. Lian\\_xu@163.com.\n\n-   PMID: **39112955**\n-   PMCID: [PMC11304927](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC11304927/)\n-   DOI: [10.1186/s12905-024-03285-8](https://doi.org/10.1186/s12905-024-03285-8)\n\nItem in Clipboard\n\nReview\n\n# Pseudo-Meigs syndrome caused by a rapidly enlarging hydropic leiomyoma with elevated CA125 levels mimicking ovarian malignancy: a case report and literature review\n\nLongquan Zou et al. BMC Womens Health. 2024.\n\nShow details\n\nDisplay options\n\nDisplay options\n\nFormat Abstract PubMed PMID\n\nBMC Womens Health\n\nActions\n\n-   [Search in PubMed](/?term=%22BMC+Womens+Health%22%5Bjour%5D&sort=date&sort_order=desc)\n-   [Search in NLM Catalog](https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/nlmcatalog?term=%22BMC+Womens+Health%22%5BTitle+Abbreviation%5D)\n-   [Add to Search](#)\n\n. 2024 Aug 7;24(1):445.\n\ndoi: 10.1186/s12905-024-03285-8.\n\n### Authors\n\n[Longquan Zou](/?term=Zou+L&cauthor_id=39112955)  [1](#short-view-affiliation-1 \"Department of Pathology, Zigong Fourth People's Hospital, Zigong, Sichuan, China.\")   [2](#short-view-affiliation-2 \"Institute of Precision Medicine, Zigong Academy of Medical Big Data and Artificial Intelligence, Zigong, Sichuan, China.\") , [Jinlong Lou](/?term=Lou+J&cauthor_id=39112955)  [1](#short-view-affiliation-1 \"Department of Pathology, Zigong Fourth People's Hospital, Zigong, Sichuan, China.\")   [3](#short-view-affiliation-3 \"Department of General Surgery, Zigong Fourth People's Hospital, Zigong, Sichuan, China.\") , [Haoran Huang](/?term=Huang+H&cauthor_id=39112955)  [4](#short-view-affiliation-4 \"College of Biomedical Engineering, Chongqing Medical University, Chongqing, China.\") , [Lian Xu](/?term=Xu+L&cauthor_id=39112955)  [5](#short-view-affiliation-5 \"Department of Pathology, Key Laboratory of Birth Defects and Related Diseases of Women and Children of MOE, West China Second University Hospital, Sichuan University, Chengdu, Sichuan, China. Lian_xu@163.com.\")\n\n### Affiliations\n\n-   1 Department of Pathology, Zigong Fourth People's Hospital, Zigong, Sichuan, China.\n-   2 Institute of Precision Medicine, Zigong Academy of Medical Big Data and Artificial Intelligence, Zigong, Sichuan, China.\n-   3 Department of General Surgery, Zigong Fourth People's Hospital, Zigong, Sichuan, China.\n-   4 College of Biomedical Engineering, Chongqing Medical University, Chongqing, China.\n-   5 Department of Pathology, Key Laboratory of Birth Defects and Related Diseases of Women and Children of MOE, West China Second University Hospital, Sichuan University, Chengdu, Sichuan, China. Lian\\_xu@163.com.\n\n-   PMID: **39112955**\n-   PMCID: [PMC11304927](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC11304927/)\n-   DOI: [10.1186/s12905-024-03285-8](https://doi.org/10.1186/s12905-024-03285-8)\n\nItem in Clipboard\n\nFull text links Cite\n\nDisplay options\n\nDisplay options\n\nFormat AbstractPubMedPMID\n\n## Abstract\n\nPseudo-Meigs syndrome is a rare syndrome characterized by hydrothorax and ascites associated with pelvic masses, and patients occasionally present with elevated serum cancer antigen-125 (CA125) levels. Hydropic leiomyoma (HLM) is an uncommon subtype of uterine leiomyoma characterized by hydropic degeneration and secondary cystic changes. Rapidly enlarging HLMs accompanied by hydrothorax, ascites, and elevated CA125 levels may be misdiagnosed as malignant tumors. Here, we report a case of HLM in a 45-year-old Chinese woman who presented with ascites and hydrothorax. Preoperative abdominopelvic CT revealed a giant solid mass in the fundus uteri measuring 20 × 15 × 12 cm. Her serum CA125 level was elevated to 247.7 U/ml, while her hydrothorax CA125 level was 304.60 U/ml. The patient was initially diagnosed with uterine malignancy and underwent total abdominal hysterectomy and adhesiolysis. Pathological examination confirmed the presence of a uterine hydropic leiomyoma with cystic changes. After tumor removal, the ascites and hydrothorax subsided quickly, with no evidence of recurrence. The patient's serum CA125 level decreased to 116.90 U/mL on Day 7 and 5.6 U/mL on Day 40 postsurgery. Follow-up data were obtained at 6 months, 1 year, and 2 years after surgery, and no recurrence of ascites or hydrothorax was observed. This case highlights the importance of accurate diagnosis and appropriate management of HLM to achieve successful outcomes.\n\n**Keywords:** CA125; Hydropic leiomyoma; Pseudo-Meigs syndrome.\n\n© 2024. The Author(s).\n\n[PubMed Disclaimer](/disclaimer/)\n\n## Conflict of interest statement\n\nThe authors declare no competing interests.\n\n## Figures\n\n [![Fig. 1](https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/6c29/11304927/d4130bffd810/12905_2024_3285_Fig1_HTML.gif)](https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/6c29/11304927/2f35f2cd35cf/12905_2024_3285_Fig1_HTML.jpg) \n\n**\n\nFig. 1\n\n**\n\nContrast-enhanced CT (coronal view) revealed…\n\n**\n\nFig. 1\n\n**\n\nContrast-enhanced CT (coronal view) revealed a giant mass measuring 14 × 12 ×…\n\n**Fig. 1**\n\nContrast-enhanced CT (coronal view) revealed a giant mass measuring 14 × 12 × 10 cm in size in the pelvis, with heterogeneous and intense enhancement, a scattered low-density edema area, and a cyst in the center (blue arrow), and massive ascites and a right-sided hydrothorax were observed (red arrow)\n\n [![Fig. 2](https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/6c29/11304927/02f3727fbb55/12905_2024_3285_Fig2_HTML.gif)](https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/6c29/11304927/d08e92c5efbe/12905_2024_3285_Fig2_HTML.jpg) \n\n**\n\nFig. 2\n\n**\n\nContrast-enhanced CT (sagittal view) revealed…\n\n**\n\nFig. 2\n\n**\n\nContrast-enhanced CT (sagittal view) revealed a giant mass measuring 14 × 12 ×…\n\n**Fig. 2**\n\nContrast-enhanced CT (sagittal view) revealed a giant mass measuring 14 × 12 × 10 cm in size in the pelvis, with a noted cyst in the center (blue arrow)\n\n [![Fig. 3](https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/6c29/11304927/2478e513e4c3/12905_2024_3285_Fig3_HTML.gif)](https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/6c29/11304927/d663608f0c49/12905_2024_3285_Fig3_HTML.jpg) \n\n**\n\nFig. 3\n\n**\n\nGross examination revealed a solid…\n\n**\n\nFig. 3\n\n**\n\nGross examination revealed a solid grayish-white tumor located at the uterine fundus that…\n\n**Fig. 3**\n\nGross examination revealed a solid grayish-white tumor located at the uterine fundus that protruded into the pelvic cavity (blue arrow). The cut surface was grayish-white and fleshy with water degeneration and cystic changes (red arrow)\n\n [![Fig. 4](https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/6c29/11304927/b630b7a2430d/12905_2024_3285_Fig4_HTML.gif)](https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/6c29/11304927/3bebb6aff491/12905_2024_3285_Fig4_HTML.jpg) \n\n**\n\nFig. 4\n\n**\n\nThe tumor was composed of…\n\n**\n\nFig. 4\n\n**\n\nThe tumor was composed of spindle cells arranged in intersecting fascicles. The cells…\n\n**Fig. 4**\n\nThe tumor was composed of spindle cells arranged in intersecting fascicles. The cells had eosinophilic cytoplasm and cigar-shaped nuclei with small nucleoli, absent mitoses, and hemorrhagic necrosis (HE, 40X)\n\n [![Fig. 5](https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/6c29/11304927/2d1d84a188ce/12905_2024_3285_Fig5_HTML.gif)](https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/6c29/11304927/f6c4e27af5df/12905_2024_3285_Fig5_HTML.jpg) \n\n**\n\nFig. 5\n\n**\n\nNoted edema areas or an…\n\n**\n\nFig. 5\n\n**\n\nNoted edema areas or an extracellular watery matrix were observed in the tumor…\n\n**Fig. 5**\n\nNoted edema areas or an extracellular watery matrix were observed in the tumor (HE, 100X)\n\n [![Fig. 6](https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/6c29/11304927/19a659f622d7/12905_2024_3285_Fig6_HTML.gif)](https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/6c29/11304927/4a337a318074/12905_2024_3285_Fig6_HTML.jpg) \n\n**\n\nFig. 6\n\n**\n\nImmunohistochemical staining revealed that the…\n\n**\n\nFig. 6\n\n**\n\nImmunohistochemical staining revealed that the tumor cells were positive for h-Caldesmon (EnVision, 200X)\n\n**Fig. 6**\n\nImmunohistochemical staining revealed that the tumor cells were positive for h-Caldesmon (EnVision, 200X)\n\n[See this image and copyright information in PMC](#)\n\n## References\n\n1.  1.  Dunn JS, Anderson CD, Method MW, Brost BC. Hydropic degenerating leiomyoma presenting as Pseudo-meigs syndrome with elevated CA 125. Obstet Gynecol. 1998;92(4 Pt 2):648–9. - [PubMed](/9764648/)\n2.  1.  Okazaki A, Nishi K, Kasahara K. Pseudo-meigs syndrome caused by cancer of the uterine corpus. Am J Obstet Gynecol. 2019;221:71–2. 10.1016/j.ajog.2018.12.009 - [DOI](https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ajog.2018.12.009) - [PubMed](/30527943/)\n3.  1.  Feldman ED, Hughes MS, Stratton P, Schrump DS, Alexander HR. Pseudo-meigs’ syndrome secondary to isolated colorectal metastasis to ovary: a case report and review of the literature. Gynecol Oncol. 2004;93:248–51. 10.1016/j.ygyno.2003.12.025 - [DOI](https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ygyno.2003.12.025) - [PubMed](/15047245/)\n4.  1.  Loizzi V, Cormio G, Resta L, Fattizzi N, Vicino M, Selvaggi L. Pseudo-meigs syndrome and elevated CA125 associated with struma ovarii. Gynecol Oncol. 2005;97:282–4. 10.1016/j.ygyno.2004.12.040 - [DOI](https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ygyno.2004.12.040) - [PubMed](/15790478/)\n5.  1.  Yaguchi A, Ban K, Koshida Y, Fujikami Y, Ogura E, Terada A, et al. Pseudo-meigs Syndrome caused by a giant uterine leiomyoma with cystic degeneration: a Case Report. J Nippon Med Sch Nippon Ika Daigaku Zasshi. 2020;87:80–6. 10.1272/jnms.JNMS.2020\\_87-205 - [DOI](https://doi.org/10.1272/jnms.jnms.2020_87-205) - [PubMed](/31902853/)\n\nShow all 45 references\n\n## Publication types\n\n-   Case Reports\n    \n    Actions\n    