ex.php?title=Uterus&action=history)\n\nGeneral\n\n-   [What links here](/wiki/Special:WhatLinksHere/Uterus \"List of all English Wikipedia pages containing links to this page [j]\")\n-   [Related changes](/wiki/Special:RecentChangesLinked/Uterus \"Recent changes in pages linked from this page [k]\")\n-   [Upload file](//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:File_Upload_Wizard \"Upload files [u]\")\n-   [Permanent link](/w/index.php?title=Uterus&oldid=1351512539 \"Permanent link to this revision of this page\")\n-   [Page information](/w/index.php?title=Uterus&action=info \"More information about this page\")\n-   [Cite this page](/w/index.php?title=Special:CiteThisPage&page=Uterus&id=1351512539&wpFormIdentifier=titleform \"Information on how to cite this page\")\n-   [Get shortened URL](/w/index.php?title=Special:UrlShortener&url=https%3A%2F%2Fen.wikipedia.org%2Fwiki%2FUterus)\n\nPrint/export\n\n-   [Download as PDF](/w/index.php?title=Special:DownloadAsPdf&page=Uterus&action=show-download-screen \"Download this page as a PDF file\")\n-   [Printable version](/w/index.php?title=Uterus&printable=yes \"Printable version of this page [p]\")\n\nIn other projects\n\n-   [Wikimedia Commons](https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/Category:Uterus)\n-   [Wikiquote](https://en.wikiquote.org/wiki/Uterus)\n-   [Wikidata item](https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Special:EntityPage/Q9612 \"Structured data on this page hosted by Wikidata [g]\")\n\nAppearance\n\nmove to sidebar hide\n\nFrom Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia\n\nFemale sex organ in mammals\n\n\"Womb\" redirects here. For other uses, see [Womb (disambiguation)](/wiki/Womb_\\(disambiguation\\) \"Womb (disambiguation)\"). \"In utero\" redirects here. For the album by Nirvana, see [*In Utero*](/wiki/In_Utero \"In Utero\"). \"Uterine\" redirects here. For maternal half-siblings, see [Uterine siblings](/wiki/Uterine_siblings \"Uterine siblings\"). \"Intrauterine\" redirects here. For the contraceptive devices, see [Intrauterine device](/wiki/Intrauterine_device \"Intrauterine device\"). \"Hystera\" redirects here; not to be confused with [Hysteria](/wiki/Hysteria \"Hysteria\").\n\nUterus\n\n[![](//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/72/Illu_cervix.svg/330px-Illu_cervix.svg.png)](/wiki/File:Illu_cervix.svg)\n\nDiagram of human uterus and surrounding structures\n\nDetails\n\n[Precursor](/wiki/Embryology \"Embryology\")\n\n[Paramesonephric ducts](/wiki/Paramesonephric_duct \"Paramesonephric duct\")\n\n[System](/wiki/Organ_system \"Organ system\")\n\n[Reproductive system](/wiki/Reproductive_system \"Reproductive system\")\n\n[Artery](/wiki/Artery \"Artery\")\n\n[Ovarian artery](/wiki/Ovarian_artery \"Ovarian artery\") and [uterine artery](/wiki/Uterine_artery \"Uterine artery\")\n\n[Vein](/wiki/Vein \"Vein\")\n\n[Uterine veins](/wiki/Uterine_veins \"Uterine veins\")\n\n[Lymph](/wiki/Lymph \"Lymph\")\n\nBody and cervix to [internal iliac lymph nodes](/wiki/Internal_iliac_lymph_nodes \"Internal iliac lymph nodes\"), fundus to [para-aortic lymph nodes](/wiki/Para-aortic_lymph_nodes \"Para-aortic lymph nodes\"), lumbar and superficial inguinal lymph nodes\n\nIdentifiers\n\n[Latin](/wiki/Latin \"Latin\")\n\n*uterus*\n\n[Greek](/wiki/Ancient_Greek \"Ancient Greek\")\n\n*ὑστέρα (hystéra)*\n\n[MeSH](/wiki/Medical_Subject_Headings \"Medical Subject Headings\")\n\n[D014599](https://meshb.nlm.nih.gov/record/ui?ui=D014599)\n\n[TA98](/wiki/Terminologia_Anatomica \"Terminologia Anatomica\")\n\n[A09.1.03.001](https://ifaa.unifr.ch/Public/EntryPage/TA98%20Tree/Entity%20TA98%20EN/09.1.03.001%20Entity%20TA98%20EN.htm)\n\n[TA2](/wiki/Terminologia_Anatomica \"Terminologia Anatomica\")\n\n[3500](https://ta2viewer.openanatomy.org/?id=3500)\n\n[FMA](/wiki/Foundational_Model_of_Anatomy \"Foundational Model of Anatomy\")\n\n[17558](https://bioportal.bioontology.org/ontologies/FMA/?p=classes&conceptid=http%3A%2F%2Fpurl.org%2Fsig%2Font%2Ffma%2Ffma17558)\n\n[Anatomical terminology](/wiki/Anatomical_terminology \"Anatomical terminology\")\n\n\\[[edit on Wikidata](https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q9612 \"d:Q9612\")\\]\n\nThe **uterus** (from [Latin](/wiki/Latin \"Latin\") *uterus*, pl.: **uteri** or **uteruses**) or **womb** ([/wuːm/](/wiki/Help:IPA/English \"Help:IPA/English\")) is the [organ](/wiki/Hollow_organ \"Hollow organ\") in the [reproductive system](/wiki/Reproductive_system \"Reproductive system\") of most [female](/wiki/Female \"Female\") [mammals](/wiki/Mammal \"Mammal\"), including humans, that accommodates the [embryonic](/wiki/Embryonic_development \"Embryonic development\") and [fetal development](/wiki/Prenatal_development \"Prenatal development\") of one or more [fertilized eggs](/wiki/Fertilized_egg \"Fertilized egg\") until [birth](/wiki/Birth \"Birth\").[\\[1\\]](#cite_note-1) The uterus is a [hormone](/wiki/Hormone \"Hormone\")\\-responsive [sex organ](/wiki/Sex_organ \"Sex organ\") that contains [glands](/wiki/Uterine_gland \"Uterine gland\") in its [lining](/wiki/Endometrium \"Endometrium\") that secrete [uterine milk](/wiki/Uterine_milk \"Uterine milk\") for embryonic nourishment. (The term *uterus* is also applied to analogous structures in some non-mammalian animals.)\n\nIn humans, the lower end of the uterus is a narrow part known as the [isthmus](/wiki/Uterine_isthmus \"Uterine isthmus\") that connects to the [cervix](/wiki/Cervix \"Cervix\"), the anterior gateway leading to the [vagina](/wiki/Vagina \"Vagina\"). The upper end, the body of the uterus, is connected to the [fallopian tubes](/wiki/Fallopian_tubes \"Fallopian tubes\") at the [uterine horns](/wiki/Uterine_horns \"Uterine horns\"); the rounded part, the fundus, is above the openings to the fallopian tubes. The connection of the [uterine cavity](/wiki/Uterine_cavity \"Uterine cavity\") with a fallopian tube is called the [uterotubal junction](/wiki/Uterotubal_junction \"Uterotubal junction\"). The [fertilized egg](/wiki/Zygote \"Zygote\") is carried to the uterus along the fallopian tube. It will have [divided](/wiki/Cleavage_\\(embryo\\) \"Cleavage (embryo)\") on its journey to form a [blastocyst](/wiki/Blastocyst \"Blastocyst\") that will [implant](/wiki/Implantation_\\(embryology\\) \"Implantation (embryology)\") itself into the lining of the uterus – the [endometrium](/wiki/Endometrium \"Endometrium\"), where it will receive nutrients and develop into the [embryo](/wiki/Embryo \"Embryo\") proper, and later [fetus](/wiki/Fetus \"Fetus\"), for the duration of the [pregnancy](/wiki/Pregnancy \"Pregnancy\").\n\nIn the [human embryo](/wiki/Human_embryonic_development \"Human embryonic development\"), the uterus develops from the [paramesonephric ducts](/wiki/Paramesonephric_duct \"Paramesonephric duct\"), which fuse into the single organ known as a simplex uterus. The uterus has different forms in many other animals, and in some, it exists as two separate uteri known as a duplex uterus.\n\nIn [medicine](/wiki/Medicine \"Medicine\") and related professions, the term *uterus* is consistently used, while the [Germanic](/wiki/Germanic_languages \"Germanic languages\")\\-derived term *[womb](https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/womb \"wikt:womb\")* is commonly used in everyday contexts. Events occurring within the uterus are described with the term ***in utero***.\n\n## Structure\n\n\\[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Uterus&action=edit&section=1 \"Edit section: Structure\")\\]\n\n[![Different regions of the uterus displayed and labelled using a 3D medical animation still shot](//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/97/3D_Medical_Animation_Uterus.jpg/330px-3D_Medical_Animation_Uterus.jpg)](/wiki/File:3D_Medical_Animation_Uterus.jpg)\n\nDifferent regions of the uterus, and the [vagina](/wiki/Vagina \"Vagina\"), displayed and labelled using a 3D medical illustration\n\nIn humans, the uterus is located within the [pelvic region](/wiki/Pelvis \"Pelvis\") immediately behind and almost overlying the [bladder](/wiki/Urinary_bladder \"Urinary bladder\"), and in front of the [sigmoid colon](/wiki/Sigmoid_colon \"Sigmoid colon\"). The human uterus is pear-shaped and about 7.6 cm (3.0 in) long, 4.5 cm (1.8 in) broad (side to side), and 3.0 cm (1.2 in) thick.[\\[2\\]](#cite_note-Manual_of_Obstetrics-2)[\\[3\\]](#cite_note-3) A typical adult uterus weighs about 60 grams. The uterus can be divided anatomically into four regions: the **fundus** – the uppermost rounded portion of the uterus above the openings of the [fallopian tubes](/wiki/Fallopian_tube \"Fallopian tube\"),[\\[4\\]](#cite_note-openstax-4) the **body**, the [cervix](/wiki/Cervix \"Cervix\"), and the [cervical canal](/wiki/Cervical_canal \"Cervical canal\"). The cervix protrudes into the [vagina](/wiki/Vagina \"Vagina\"). The uterus is held in position within the pelvis by [ligaments](/wiki/Ligaments \"Ligaments\"), which are part of the [endopelvic fascia](/wiki/Endopelvic_fascia \"Endopelvic fascia\"). These ligaments include the [pubocervical ligaments](/wiki/Pubocervical_ligaments \"Pubocervical ligaments\"), the [cardinal ligaments](/wiki/Cardinal_ligament \"Cardinal ligament\"), and the [uterosacral ligaments](/wiki/Uterosacral_ligament \"Uterosacral ligament\"). It is covered by a sheet-like fold of peritoneum, the [broad ligament](/wiki/Broad_ligament \"Broad ligament\").[\\[5\\]](#cite_note-5)\n\n### Layers\n\n\\[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Uterus&action=edit&section=2 \"Edit section: Layers\")\\]\n\nUterine wall thickness[\\[6\\]](#cite_note-6)\n\nLocation\n\nMean (mm)\n\nRange (mm)\n\nAnterior wall\n\n23\n\n17 - 25\n\nPosterior wall\n\n21\n\n15 - 25\n\nFundus\n\n20\n\n15 - 22\n\nIsthmus\n\n10\n\n8 - 22\n\n[![](//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/28/Gray1169.png/250px-Gray1169.png)](/wiki/File:Gray1169.png)\n\nVertical section of mucous membrane of human uterus\n\nThe uterus has three layers, which together form the **uterine wall**. From innermost to outermost, these layers are the [endometrium](/wiki/Endometrium \"Endometrium\"), [myometrium](/wiki/Myometrium \"Myometrium\"), and [perimetrium](/wiki/Perimetrium \"Perimetrium\").[\\[7\\]](#cite_note-T_and_D-7)\n\nThe endometrium is the inner [epithelial layer](/wiki/Epithelium \"Epithelium\"), along with its [mucous membrane](/wiki/Mucous_membrane \"Mucous membrane\"), of the [mammalian](/wiki/Mammal \"Mammal\") uterus. It has a basal layer and a functional layer; the functional layer thickens and then is shed during the [menstrual cycle](/wiki/Menstrual_cycle \"Menstrual cycle\") or [estrous cycle](/wiki/Estrous_cycle \"Estrous cycle\"). During [pregnancy](/wiki/Pregnancy \"Pregnancy\"), the [uterine glands](/wiki/Uterine_gland \"Uterine gland\") and [blood vessels](/wiki/Blood_vessel \"Blood vessel\") in the endometrium further increase in size and number and form the [decidua](/wiki/Decidua \"Decidua\"). Vascular spaces fuse and become interconnected, forming the [placenta](/wiki/Placenta \"Placenta\"), which supplies [oxygen](/wiki/Oxygen \"Oxygen\") and nutrition to the [embryo](/wiki/Embryo \"Embryo\") and [fetus](/wiki/Fetus \"Fetus\").[\\[8\\]](#cite_note-histology-8)[\\[9\\]](#cite_note-Guyton2006-9)\n\nThe myometrium of the uterus mostly consists of [smooth muscle](/wiki/Smooth_muscle \"Smooth muscle\"). The innermost layer of myometrium is known as the **junctional zone**, which becomes thickened in [adenomyosis](/wiki/Adenomyosis \"Adenomyosis\").[\\[10\\]](#cite_note-10)\n\nThe perimetrium is a [serous](/wiki/Serous_membrane \"Serous membrane\") layer of visceral [peritoneum](/wiki/Peritoneum \"Peritoneum\"). It covers the outer surface of the uterus.[\\[11\\]](#cite_note-11)\n\nSurrounding the uterus is a layer or band of fibrous and fatty connective tissue called the [parametrium](/wiki/Parametrium \"Parametrium\") that connects the uterus to other tissues of the pelvis.\n\n[Commensal](/wiki/Commensalism \"Commensalism\") and [mutualistic](/wiki/Mutualism_\\(biology\\) \"Mutualism (biology)\") organisms are present in the uterus and form the [uterine microbiome](/wiki/Uterine_microbiome \"Uterine microbiome\").[\\[12\\]](#cite_note-FranasiakScott2015-12)[\\[13\\]](#cite_note-Verstrael6-13)[\\[14\\]](#cite_note-MorKwon2015-14)[\\[15\\]](#cite_note-PayneBayatibojakhi2014-15)\n\n### Support\n\n\\[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Uterus&action=edit&section=3 \"Edit section: Support\")\\]\n\n[![](//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5c/Gray1161.png/250px-Gray1161.png)](/wiki/File:Gray1161.png)\n\nUterus covered by the broad ligament\n\nThe uterus is primarily supported by the [pelvic diaphragm](/wiki/Pelvic_diaphragm \"Pelvic diaphragm\"), [perineal body](/wiki/Perineal_body \"Perineal body\"), and [urogenital diaphragm](/wiki/Urogenital_diaphragm \"Urogenital diaphragm\"). Secondarily, it is supported by ligaments, including the [peritoneal ligament](/wiki/Peritoneal_ligament \"Peritoneal ligament\") and the [broad ligament of uterus](/wiki/Broad_ligament_of_uterus \"Broad ligament of uterus\").[\\[16\\]](#cite_note-ucc-16)\n\n#### Major ligaments\n\n\\[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Uterus&action=edit&section=4 \"Edit section: Major ligaments\")\\]\n\nThe uterus is held in place by several peritoneal ligaments, of which the following are the most important (there are two of each):\n\nName\n\nFrom\n\nTo\n\n[Uterosacral ligaments](/wiki/Uterosacral_ligaments \"Uterosacral ligaments\")\n\nPosterior cervix\n\nAnterior face of [sacrum](/wiki/Sacrum \"Sacrum\")\n\n[Cardinal ligaments](/wiki/Cardinal_ligaments \"Cardinal ligaments\")\n\nSide of the cervix\n\n[Ischial spines](/wiki/Ischial_spine \"Ischial spine\")\n\n[Pubocervical ligaments](/wiki/Pubocervical_ligaments \"Pubocervical ligaments\")[\\[16\\]](#cite_note-ucc-16)\n\nSide of the cervix\n\n[Pubic symphysis](/wiki/Pubic_symphysis \"Pubic symphysis\")\n\n### Axis\n\n\\[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Uterus&action=edit&section=5 \"Edit section: Axis\")\\]\n\nNormally, the human uterus lies in anteversion and anteflexion. In most women, the long axis of the uterus is bent forward on the long axis of the vagina, against the urinary bladder. This position is referred to as anteversion of the uterus. Furthermore, the long axis of the body of the uterus is bent forward at the level of the internal os with the long axis of the cervix. This position is termed anteflexion of the uterus.[\\[17\\]](#cite_note-17) The uterus assumes an anteverted position in 50% of women, a retroverted position in 25% of women, and a midposed position in the remaining 25% of women.[\\[2\\]](#cite_note-Manual_of_Obstetrics-2)\n\n### Position\n\n\\[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Uterus&action=edit&section=6 \"Edit section: Position\")\\]\n\n[![](//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/57/Figure_28_02_01.JPG/250px-Figure_28_02_01.JPG)](/wiki/File:Figure_28_02_01.JPG)\n\nUterus shown in position in the body\n\nThe uterus is located in the middle of the pelvic cavity, in the [frontal plane](/wiki/Frontal_plane \"Frontal plane\") (due to the [broad ligament of the uterus](/wiki/Broad_ligament_of_the_uterus \"Broad ligament of the uterus\")). The fundus does not extend above the *[linea terminalis](/wiki/Linea_terminalis \"Linea terminalis\")*, while the vaginal part of the cervix does not extend below the [interspinal line](/w/index.php?title=Interspinal_line&action=edit&redlink=1 \"Interspinal line (page does not exist)\"). The uterus is mobile and moves posteriorly under the pressure of a full bladder, or anteriorly under the pressure of a full rectum. If both are full, it moves upwards. Increased intra-abdominal pressure pushes it downwards. The mobility is conferred to it by a musculofibrous apparatus that consists of suspensory and sustentacular parts. Under normal circumstances, the suspensory part keeps the uterus in anteflexion and anteversion (in 90% of women) and keeps it \"floating\" in the pelvis. The meanings of these terms are described below:\n\n[![](//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d7/Uterus_image-Photoroom.png/250px-Uterus_image-Photoroom.png)](/wiki/File:Uterus_image-Photoroom.png)\n\nTop-down view of the uterus and other pelvic organs, here depicted as they are usually positioned inside the body[\\[18\\]](#cite_note-18)\n\nDistinction\n\nMore common\n\nLess common\n\nPosition tipped\n\n\"Anteverted\": Tipped forward\n\n\"[Retroverted](/wiki/Retroverted_uterus \"Retroverted uterus\")\": Tipped backwards\n\nPosition of fundus\n\n\"Anteflexed\": Fundus is pointing forward relative to the cervix\n\n\"Retroflexed\": Fundus is pointing backward\n\n[![](//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/7e/Positions_of_the_human_uterus_1.png/250px-Positions_of_the_human_uterus_1.png)](/wiki/File:Positions_of_the_human_uterus_1.png)\n\n1\\. Anteversion with slight anteflexion  \n2\\. Anteversion with marked anteflexion  \n3\\. Anteversion with retrocession  \n4\\. Retroversion  \n5\\. Retroversion with retroflexion\n\nThe sustentacular part supports the pelvic organs and comprises the larger [pelvic diaphragm](/wiki/Pelvic_diaphragm \"Pelvic diaphragm\") in the back and the smaller [urogenital diaphragm](/wiki/Urogenital_diaphragm \"Urogenital diaphragm\") in the front.\n\nThe pathological changes of the position of the uterus are:\n\n-   [retroversion](/wiki/Retroverted_uterus \"Retroverted uterus\")/retroflexion, if it is fixed\n-   hyperanteflexion – tipped too forward; most commonly congenital, but may be caused by tumors\n-   anteposition, retroposition, lateroposition – the whole uterus is moved; caused by [parametritis](/wiki/Parametritis \"Parametritis\") or tumors\n-   elevation, descensus, [prolapse](/wiki/Uterine_prolapse \"Uterine prolapse\")\n-   rotation (the whole uterus rotates around its longitudinal axis), torsion (only the body of the uterus rotates around)\n-   inversion\n\nIn cases where the uterus is \"tipped\", also known as [retroverted uterus](/wiki/Retroverted_uterus \"Retroverted uterus\"), the woman may have symptoms of pain during sexual intercourse, pelvic pain during menstruation, minor incontinence, urinary tract infections, fertility difficulties,[\\[19\\]](#cite_note-19) and difficulty using tampons. A pelvic examination by a doctor can determine if a uterus is tipped.[\\[20\\]](#cite_note-20)\n\n### Blood, lymph, and nerve supply\n\n\\[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Uterus&action=edit&section=7 \"Edit section: Blood, lymph, and nerve supply\")\\]\n\n[![](//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/08/Uterine_arterial_vasculature.svg/250px-Uterine_arterial_vasculature.svg.png)](/wiki/File:Uterine_arterial_vasculature.svg)\n\nDiagram of uterine blood supply\n\nThe human uterus is supplied by arterial blood from the [uterine artery](/wiki/Uterine_artery \"Uterine artery\") and the [ovarian artery](/wiki/Ovarian_artery \"Ovarian artery\"). Another anastomotic branch may also supply the uterus from anastomosis of these two arteries.\n\nAfferent nerves supplying the uterus are [T11 and T12](/wiki/Spinal_nerves#Thoracic_nerves \"Spinal nerves\"). Sympathetic supply is from the [hypogastric plexus](/wiki/Superior_hypogastric_plexus \"Superior hypogastric plexus\") and the [ovarian plexus](/wiki/Ovarian_plexus \"Ovarian plexus\"). Parasympathetic supply is from the S2, S3, and S4 nerves.\n\n## Development\n\n\\[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Uterus&action=edit&section=8 \"Edit section: Development\")\\]\n\nMain article: [Development of the reproductive system](/wiki/Development_of_the_reproductive_system \"Development of the reproductive system\")\n\n[![](//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c0/The_uterus_differentiates_from_the_fetal_M%C3%BCllerian_ducts..jpg/250px-The_uterus_differentiates_from_the_fetal_M%C3%BCllerian_ducts..jpg)](/wiki/File:The_uterus_differentiates_from_the_fetal_M%C3%BCllerian_ducts..jpg)\n\nDifferentiation of uterus\n\nBilateral [Müllerian ducts](/wiki/M%C3%BCllerian_duct \"Müllerian duct\") form during early human fetal life. In males, [anti-Müllerian hormone](/wiki/Anti-M%C3%BCllerian_hormone \"Anti-Müllerian hormone\") (AMH) secreted from the testes leads to the regression of the ducts. In females, these ducts give rise to the [fallopian tubes](/wiki/Fallopian_tubes \"Fallopian tubes\") and the uterus. In humans, the lower segments of the two ducts fuse to form a single uterus; in cases of [uterine malformation](/wiki/Uterine_malformation \"Uterine malformation\"), this fusion may be disturbed. The different uterine morphologies among the mammals are due to varying degrees of fusion of the Müllerian ducts.\n\nVarious congenital conditions of the uterus can develop *in utero*. Though uncommon, some of these are [didelphic uterus](/wiki/Didelphic_uterus \"Didelphic uterus\"), [bicornate uterus](/wiki/Bicornate_uterus \"Bicornate uterus\"), and others.[\\[21\\]](#cite_note-21)\n\nSee also [List of related male and female reproductive organs](/wiki/List_of_related_male_and_female_reproductive_organs \"List of related male and female reproductive organs\").\n\n## Function\n\n\\[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Uterus&action=edit&section=9 \"Edit section: Function\")\\]\n\n[![](//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/80/Human_female_inner_genitalia.png/250px-Human_female_inner_genitalia.png)](/wiki/File:Human_female_inner_genitalia.png)\n\nMaximum penetration depth of the penis\n\nThe primary reproductive function of the human uterus is to prepare for the implantation of a [zygote](/wiki/Zygote \"Zygote\"), a fertilized [ovum](/wiki/Egg_cell \"Egg cell\"), and maintenance of pregnancy if implantation occurs.[\\[22\\]](#cite_note-Critchley-2020-22) Traveling along the [fallopian tube](/wiki/Fallopian_tube \"Fallopian tube\") on its way to the uterine cavity, the zygote divides [mitotically](/wiki/Mitosis \"Mitosis\") to become a [blastocyst](/wiki/Blastocyst \"Blastocyst\"), which ultimately attaches to the uterine wall and [implants](/wiki/Implantation_\\(embryology\\) \"Implantation (embryology)\") into the [endometrium](/wiki/Endometrium \"Endometrium\").[\\[4\\]](#cite_note-openstax-4) The [placenta](/wiki/Placenta \"Placenta\") later develops to nourish the embryo, which grows through [embryonic](/wiki/Human_embryonic_development \"Human embryonic development\") and [fetal development](/wiki/Prenatal_development \"Prenatal development\") until [childbirth](/wiki/Childbirth \"Childbirth\"). During this process, the uterus grows to accommodate the growing fetus.[\\[23\\]](#cite_note-Ameer-2023-23) When normal labor begins, the uterus forcefully contracts as the cervix dilates, which results in delivery of the infant.[\\[23\\]](#cite_note-Ameer-2023-23)\n\nIn the absence of pregnancy, [menstruation](/wiki/Menstruation \"Menstruation\") occurs.[\\[22\\]](#cite_note-Critchley-2020-22) The withdrawal of female sex hormones, [estrogen](/wiki/Estrogen \"Estrogen\") and [progesterone](/wiki/Progesterone \"Progesterone\"), which occurs in the absence of fertilization, triggers the shedding of the functional layer of the endometrium.[\\[22\\]](#cite_note-Critchley-2020-22) This layer is broken down, shed, and restored in anticipation of the next menstrual cycle.[\\[22\\]](#cite_note-Critchley-2020-22) The average bleeding duration during menses is 5–7 days after which the menstrual cycle begins again.[\\[24\\]](#cite_note-24)\n\n## Clinical significance\n\n\\[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Uterus&action=edit&section=10 \"Edit section: Clinical significance\")\\]\n\nDuring [pregnancy](/wiki/Pregnancy \"Pregnancy\"), the growth rate of the fetus can be assessed by measuring the [fundal height](/wiki/Fundal_height \"Fundal height\").\n\nSome [pathological](/wiki/Pathology \"Pathology\") states include:\n\n[![](//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/bd/Endometrial_fluid_accumulation%2C_postmenopausal.jpg/250px-Endometrial_fluid_accumulation%2C_postmenopausal.jpg)](/wiki/File:Endometrial_fluid_accumulation,_postmenopausal.jpg)\n\n[Transvaginal ultrasonography](/wiki/Transvaginal_ultrasonography \"Transvaginal ultrasonography\") showing a uterine fluid accumulation in a [postmenopausal](/wiki/Postmenopausal \"Postmenopausal\") woman\n\n-   Accumulation of fluids other than blood or of unknown constitution. One study concluded that [postmenopausal](/wiki/Postmenopausal \"Postmenopausal\") women with endometrial fluid collection on [gynecologic ultrasonography](/wiki/Gynecologic_ultrasonography \"Gynecologic ultrasonography\") should undergo [endometrial biopsy](/wiki/Endometrial_biopsy \"Endometrial biopsy\") if the endometrial lining is thicker than 3 mm or if the endometrial fluid is [echogenic](/wiki/Echogenic \"Echogenic\"). In cases of a lining 3 mm or less and clear endometrial fluid, endometrial biopsy was not regarded to be necessary, but [endocervical curettage](/wiki/Endocervical_curettage \"Endocervical curettage\") to rule out endocervical cancer was recommended.[\\[25\\]](#cite_note-25)\n-   [Hematometra](/wiki/Hematometra \"Hematometra\"), which is an accumulation of blood within the uterus.[\\[26\\]](#cite_note-26)\n-   [Prolapse of the uterus](/wiki/Uterine_prolapse \"Uterine prolapse\")\n-   [Carcinoma of the cervix](/wiki/Carcinoma_of_the_cervix \"Carcinoma of the cervix\") – malignant neoplasm\n-   [Carcinoma of the uterus](/wiki/Carcinoma_of_the_uterus \"Carcinoma of the uterus\") – malignant neoplasm\n-   [Fibroids](/wiki/Uterine_fibroids \"Uterine fibroids\") – benign neoplasms\n-   [Adenomyosis](/wiki/Adenomyosis \"Adenomyosis\") – ectopic growth of endometrial tissue within the myometrium\n-   [Endometritis](/wiki/Endometritis \"Endometritis\"), infection in the uterine cavity\n-   [Pyometra](/wiki/Pyometra \"Pyometra\") – infection of the uterus, most commonly seen in dogs\n-   [Asherman's syndrome](/wiki/Asherman%27s_syndrome \"Asherman's syndrome\"), also known as intrauterine [adhesions](/wiki/Adhesions \"Adhesions\"), occurs when the basal layer of the endometrium is damaged by instrumentation (e.g., [D&C](/wiki/Dilation_and_curettage \"Dilation and curettage\")) or infection (e.g., endometrial [tuberculosis](/wiki/Tuberculosis \"Tuberculosis\")), resulting in endometrial scarring followed by adhesion formation that partially or completely obliterates the uterine cavity\n-   Myometritis – inflammation of the muscular uterine wall.[\\[27\\]](#cite_note-27)\n\n### Malformations\n\n\\[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Uterus&action=edit&section=11 \"Edit section: Malformations\")\\]\n\n[![](//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8e/Uterine_malformation.jpg/250px-Uterine_malformation.jpg)](/wiki/File:Uterine_malformation.jpg)\n\nFour types of [uterine malformation](/wiki/Uterine_malformation \"Uterine malformation\")\n\n[Uterine malformations](/wiki/Uterine_malformation \"Uterine malformation\") are mainly [congenital malformations](/wiki/Birth_defect \"Birth defect\"), and include *[uterus didelphys](/wiki/Uterus_didelphys \"Uterus didelphys\")*, [bicornuate uterus](/wiki/Bicornuate_uterus \"Bicornuate uterus\") and [septate uterus](/wiki/Septate_uterus \"Septate uterus\"). Congenital absence of the uterus is known as [Müllerian agenesis](/wiki/M%C3%BCllerian_agenesis \"Müllerian agenesis\").\n\n### Surgery\n\n\\[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Uterus&action=edit&section=12 \"Edit section: Surgery\")\\]\n\nA [hysterectomy](/wiki/Hysterectomy \"Hysterectomy\") is the surgical removal of the uterus, which may be carried out for several reasons, including the ridding of [tumours](/wiki/Neoplasm \"Neoplasm\"), both benign and [malignant](/wiki/Cancer \"Cancer\"). A complete hysterectomy involves the removal of the body, fundus, and cervix of the uterus. A partial hysterectomy may just involve the removal of the uterine body while leaving the cervix intact. It is the most commonly performed [gynecological surgical procedure](/wiki/Gynecological_surgery \"Gynecological surgery\").\n\n### Transplants\n\n\\[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Uterus&action=edit&section=13 \"Edit section: Transplants\")\\]\n\n[Uterus transplantation](/wiki/Uterus_transplantation \"Uterus transplantation\") has been successfully carried out in a number of countries. The transplant is intended to be temporary – recipients will have to undergo a [hysterectomy](/wiki/Hysterectomy \"Hysterectomy\") after one or two successful pregnancies. This is done to avoid the need to take [immunosuppressive drugs](/wiki/Immunosuppressive_drug \"Immunosuppressive drug\") for life with a consequent increased risk of infection.[\\[28\\]](#cite_note-28)\n\nThe procedure remains the last resort: it is, as of 2023, a relatively new and somewhat experimental procedure, performed only by certain specialist surgeons in select centres, it is expensive and unlikely to be covered by insurance, and it involves risk of infection and organ rejection. Some [ethics](/wiki/Ethics \"Ethics\") specialists consider the risks to a live donor too great, and some find the entire procedure ethically questionable, especially since the transplant is not a life-saving procedure.[\\[29\\]](#cite_note-29)[\\[30\\]](#cite_note-30)[\\[31\\]](#cite_note-31)\n\n## Other animals\n\n\\[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Uterus&action=edit&section=14 \"Edit section: Other animals\")\\]\n\nMost animals that lay [eggs](/wiki/Egg_\\(biology\\) \"Egg (biology)\"), such as [birds](/wiki/Bird \"Bird\") and [reptiles](/wiki/Reptile \"Reptile\"), including most [ovoviviparous](/wiki/Ovoviviparity \"Ovoviviparity\") species, have an [oviduct](/wiki/Oviduct \"Oviduct\") instead of a uterus. However, recent research into the biology of the [viviparous](/wiki/Viviparity \"Viviparity\") (not merely [ovoviviparous](/wiki/Ovoviviparity \"Ovoviviparity\")) [skink](/wiki/Skink \"Skink\") *[Trachylepis](/wiki/Trachylepis \"Trachylepis\") ivensi* has revealed development of a very close analogue to [eutherian](/wiki/Eutheria \"Eutheria\") mammalian placental development.[\\[32\\]](#cite_note-32)\n\nIn [monotremes](/wiki/Monotreme \"Monotreme\"), mammals which lay eggs, namely the [platypus](/wiki/Platypus \"Platypus\") and the [echidnas](/wiki/Echidna \"Echidna\"), either the term *uterus* or *oviduct* is used to describe the same organ, but the egg does not develop a [placenta](/wiki/Placenta \"Placenta\") within the mother and thus does not receive further nourishment after formation and [fertilization](/wiki/Fertilization \"Fertilization\").\n\n[Marsupials](/wiki/Marsupials \"Marsupials\") have two uteri, each of which connects to a lateral vagina, and both use a third, middle \"vagina\", which functions as the birth canal.[\\[33\\]](#cite_note-Tyndale-BiscoeRenfree1987-33)[\\[34\\]](#cite_note-Nowak1999-34) Marsupial [embryos](/wiki/Embryo \"Embryo\") form a [choriovitelline placenta](/wiki/Choriovitelline_placenta \"Choriovitelline placenta\") (which can be thought of as something between a monotreme egg and a \"true\" placenta), in which the egg's yolk sac supplies a large part of the embryo's nutrition but also attaches to the uterine wall and takes nutrients from the mother's bloodstream. However, [bandicoots](/wiki/Bandicoots \"Bandicoots\") also have a rudimentary chorioallantoic placenta, similar to those of placentals.\n\nThe [fetus](/wiki/Fetus \"Fetus\") usually develops fully in [placentals](/wiki/Placentalia \"Placentalia\") and only partially in [marsupials](/wiki/Marsupial \"Marsupial\") including [kangaroos](/wiki/Kangaroo \"Kangaroo\") and [opossums](/wiki/Opossum \"Opossum\"). In marsupials, the uterus forms as a duplex organ of two uteri. In monotremes such as the [platypus](/wiki/Platypus \"Platypus\"), the uterus is duplex and, rather than nurturing the embryo, secretes the shell around the egg. It is essentially identical with the [shell gland](/wiki/Oviduct \"Oviduct\") of birds and reptiles, with which the uterus is [homologous](/wiki/Homology_\\(biology\\) \"Homology (biology)\").[\\[35\\]](#cite_note-VB-35)\n\nIn mammals, the four main forms of the uterus are: duplex, bipartite, bicornuate, and simplex.[\\[36\\]](#cite_note-36)\n\nDuplex\n\nThere are two wholly separate uteri, with one oviduct each. Found in [marsupials](/wiki/Marsupial \"Marsupial\") (such as [kangaroos](/wiki/Kangaroo \"Kangaroo\"), [Tasmanian devils](/wiki/Tasmanian_devil \"Tasmanian devil\"), [opossums](/wiki/Opossum \"Opossum\"), etc.), [rodents](/wiki/Rodent \"Rodent\") (such as [mice](/wiki/Mouse \"Mouse\"), [rats](/wiki/Rat \"Rat\"), and [guinea pigs](/wiki/Guinea_pig \"Guinea pig\")), and [lagomorphs](/wiki/Lagomorphs \"Lagomorphs\") ([rabbits](/wiki/Rabbit \"Rabbit\") and [hares](/wiki/Hare \"Hare\")).\n\nBipartite\n\nThe two uteri are separate for most of their length, but share a single cervix. Found in [ruminants](/wiki/Ruminant \"Ruminant\") ([deer](/wiki/Deer \"Deer\"), including [moose](/wiki/Moose \"Moose\") and [elk](/wiki/Elk \"Elk\"), etc.), [hyraxes](/wiki/Hyrax \"Hyrax\"), [cats](/wiki/Cat \"Cat\"), and [horses](/wiki/Horse \"Horse\").\n\nBicornuate\n\nThe upper parts of the uterus remain separate, but the lower parts are fused into a single structure. Found in [dogs](/wiki/Dog \"Dog\"), [pigs](/wiki/Pig \"Pig\"), [elephants](/wiki/Elephant \"Elephant\"), [whales](/wiki/Whale \"Whale\"), [dolphins](/wiki/Dolphin \"Dolphin\"),[\\[37\\]](#cite_note-WürsigPerrin2009-37) and [tarsiers](/wiki/Tarsier \"Tarsier\"), and [strepsirrhine](/wiki/Strepsirrhini \"Strepsirrhini\") [primates](/wiki/Primate \"Primate\") among others.\n\nSimplex\n\nThe entire uterus is fused into a single organ.[\\[35\\]](#cite_note-VB-35) It is found in [higher primates](/wiki/Higher_primates \"Higher primates\"), including [humans](/wiki/Humans \"Humans\"), [chimpanzees](/wiki/Pan_\\(genus\\) \"Pan (genus)\"), and [monkeys](/wiki/Monkey \"Monkey\"). Occasionally, some individual females (including humans) may have a [bicornuate uterus](/wiki/Bicornuate_uterus \"Bicornuate uterus\"), a [uterine malformation](/wiki/Uterine_malformation \"Uterine malformation\") where the two parts of the uterus fail to fuse completely during fetal development.\n\nTwo uteri usually form initially in a female and a male fetus, and in placental mammals, they may partially or completely fuse into a single uterus, depending on the species. In many species with two uteri, only one is functional. Humans and other higher primates, such as chimpanzees, usually have a single completely fused uterus, although in some individuals, the uteri may not have completely fused.\n\n## Additional images\n\n\\[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Uterus&action=edit&section=15 \"Edit section: Additional images\")\\]\n\n-   [![Schematic frontal view of female anatomy](//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/68/Scheme_female_reproductive_system-en.svg/120px-Scheme_female_reproductive_system-en.svg.png)](/wiki/File:Scheme_female_reproductive_system-en.svg \"Schematic frontal view of female anatomy\")\n    \n    Schematic frontal view of female anatomy\n    \n-   [![Sectional plan of the gravid uterus in the third and fourth month](//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/34/Gray34.png/120px-Gray34.png)](/wiki/File:Gray34.png \"Sectional plan of the gravid uterus in the third and fourth month\")\n    \n    Sectional plan of the gravid uterus in the third and fourth month\n    \n-   [![Fetus in utero, between fifth and sixth months](//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/09/Gray38_%E2%80%93_Illustration_of_a_fetus_in_utero_between_the_fifth_and_sixth_months.png/120px-Gray38_%E2%80%93_Illustration_of_a_fetus_in_utero_between_the_fifth_and_sixth_months.png)](/wiki/File:Gray38_%E2%80%93_Illustration_of_a_fetus_in_utero_between_the_fifth_and_sixth_months.png \"Fetus in utero, between fifth and sixth months\")\n    \n    Fetus in utero, between fifth and sixth months\n    \n-   [![Uterus](//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/cd/Slide4DDD.JPG/120px-Slide4DDD.JPG)](/wiki/File:Slide4DDD.JPG \"Uterus\")\n    \n    Uterus\n    \n\n## See also\n\n\\[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Uterus&action=edit&section=16 \"Edit section: See also\")\\]\n\